rm at most 2 operations.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n2 <= nums.length <= 2000\n1 <= nums[i] <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming with memoization. The idea is to explore all possible ways to perform operations starting from different initial scores and keep track of the maximum number of operations possible for each score.\n\nHere's the step-by-step approach:\n\n1. **Define the state**: We need a function `dp(i, j, score)` that returns the maximum number of operations we can perform on the subarray `nums[i:j+1]` with the given `score`.\n\n2. **Base cases**:\n   - If `i >= j`, it means we have less than 2 elements left, so no more operations can be performed.\n   - If `i == j-1`, it means we have exactly 2 elements left. We can only perform one operation if the sum of these two elements equals the given score.\n\n3. **Transition**:\n   - We have three choices:\n     1. Delete the first two elements: `dp(i+2, j, score)` if `nums[i] + nums[i+1] == score`.\n     2. Delete the last two elements: `dp(i, j-2, score)` if `nums[j] + nums[j-1] == score`.\n     3. Delete the first and the last elements: `dp(i+1, j-1, score)` if `nums[i] + nums[j] == score`.\n   - We take the maximum of these choices plus 1 (for the current operation).\n\n4. **Memoization**: Use a dictionary to store the results of subproblems to avoid recomputation.\n\n5. **Initial calls**:\n   - We need to consider three possible initial scores:\n     - The sum of the first two elements.\n     - The sum of the last two elements.\n     - The sum of the first and the last elements.\n   - We start the DP from these initial scores and take the maximum result.\n\nHere is the implementation of the above approach:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        from functools import lru_cache\n        \n        @lru_cache(None)\n        def dp(i, j, score):\n            if i >= j:\n                return 0\n            if i == j - 1:\n                return 1 if nums[i] + nums[j] == score else 0\n            \n            max_ops = 0\n            if nums[i] + nums[i + 1] == score:\n                max_ops = max(max_ops, 1 + dp(i + 2, j, score))\n            if nums[j] + nums[j - 1] == score:\n                max_ops = max(max_ops, 1 + dp(i, j - 2, score))\n            if nums[i] + nums[j] == score:\n                max_ops = max(max_ops, 1 + dp(i + 1, j - 1, score))\n            \n            return max_ops\n        \n        n = len(nums)\n        if n < 2:\n            return 0\n        \n        # Try starting with the first two elements\n        score1 = nums[0] + nums[1]\n        # Try starting with the last two elements\n        score2 = nums[n - 1] + nums[n - 2]\n        # Try starting with the first and the last elements\n        score3 = nums[0] + nums[n - 1]\n        \n        return max(dp(0, n - 1, score1), dp(0, n - 1, score2), dp(0, n - 1, score3))\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently explores all possible ways to perform operations and uses memoization to avoid redundant calculations, ensuring that it runs within the constraints provided.", "estimated_date": 1707609600000}